defaultFour NI Banks collaboration / collusionsdefault in reducingdefault operating costsdefault via unethical meansdefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultA major part of the ‘structure’ of the traditional main ‘big four’ Northern Ireland banks (Bank of Ireland, Danske Bank, First Trust Bank and Ulster Bank) in relation to the retail branch and other office
defaults networks throughout Northern Ireland is a 
defaultsub structure relating to 
defaultcombined 
defaultoperating costs relating to the whole across Northern Ireland networks of the ‘big four’ NI banks, 
defaultthe purpose of which is to reduce individual / sole bank operating costs in 
defaultrelation to same and thus to derive the financial benefit from the collaboration referred to.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, it is in this particular area in which the 4 NI banks have not only collectively engaged in highly dubious and unacceptable practices of a nature which 
defaultno ethically operating organisation should ever engage, but in doing so it could be suggested that the circumstances have rendered the UK Taxpayer / UK Government (and the ROI Taxpayer / ROI Government) complicit in those same highly dubious, unethical and
default unacceptable practices. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere are relationships which have or continue to prevail(ed) which would be considered by many to be ‘inappropriate’ and unacceptable, for reasons re which it must be assumed that the resultant financial benefits to each of the 
default‘big four’ NI banks were the overriding factor regarding why the relationships prevailed / prevail, but in connection to which, in consideration of a number of relevant factors, further benefits to individuals within ‘big four’ NI  banks cannot be discount
defaulted.  
default&#xa0;
defaultPractices referred to run contrary to those principles and standards referred to in a number of UK Government publications, including the most recent and highly relevant September 2013 HM Government published document entitled
default ‘Good Business - Imdefaultplementing the UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights’ default(ref: Cm 8695), in which it is stated that this document, foreworded by The Minister of State for Business Innovation and Skills and The President of the UK Board of Trade, Right Honorable 
defaultDr Vince Cable MP and The Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs, Rightt Honourable William Hague MP, 
defaultis
default 
default‘Presented to Parliament by the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs by Command of Her Majesty (Queen Elizabeth II)’default.default&#xa0;defaultOf particular
default interest within this document is section in which reference is made to 
default‘the activities of UK State-owned, controlled or supported enterprises’default, a group to which the bailed out and currently circa 82% UK Taxpayer owned RBS, owner of the NI / ROI operating 
defaultUlster Bank, belongs.    
default&#xa0;
defaultWithin the banking sector there is no question that highly paid regulators did not regulate and law enforcement and Serious Fraud Office officers failed to enforce and to hold to account, with some of those who failed in their hi
defaultghly paid roles going on to ever better paid positions within those organisations they failed to regulate or hold to account
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultH
defaultowever it cannot be overlooked that it was banks which systematically committed frauds and various deceptions, aided and abetted
default possibly by ‘sympathetic’
default and / or compliant 
defaultentities from within ‘the system’.  
default&#xa0;
defaultIt would appear that where one, a combination of or all of the
default 
default‘big four’ NI banks and RBS have engaged in sharp practice and are challenged in connection to same, it is routine to, where responses are provided, 
defaultin connection to dubious procurement and related ‘processes’, 
defaultto use references such as 
default‘robust’ defaultand to ref
defaulter also to
default ‘independent audit(s’default) and 
default‘investigation’ defaultprocesses, with a consistent lack of evidence that such processes are actually carried out, a position which is followed by a consistent refusal to address any issues to which disingenuous and misleadin
defaultg information is provided.   
default&#xa0;
defaultTo date the citizens of UK and Northern Ireland, and indeed in a number of jurisdictions around the world, have seen little or no evidence of those within the banking sector who have committed or been complicit to sharp pra
defaultctices, deceptions, fraud, etc being held to account, with many of those individuals, or the banks they work for, continuing to operate along a very much business as usual basis, such is the lack of concern some appear to have regarding being held accounta
defaultble for any misdemeanours they may be connected to or complicit in. 
