defaultOverviewdefault&#xa0;
defaultWhilst this communication relates to a specific service sector, it cannot be assumed that the ‘principles’ which apply within 
defaulta
default specific service sector are not repeated on the same basis in other areas, especially where  there are financial benefits to be 
defaulthad by either one, several or all of the ‘big four’ NI banks
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is evidence that some NI government bodies or individuals from within those bodies may be aware of practices and collusions alluded to within this document, but as in internal NI banki
defaultng circles, have may have chosen to take a ‘blind eye / turn the other way’ approach for reasons / agendas unknown, but possibly at best, due to general apathy
default 
defaultand lack of interest
default and concern, or at worst, due possibly to personal or other relationships i
defaultnvolving senior NI banking executives.   
default&#xa0;
defaultThe citizens of Northern Ireland and UK (and of other jurisdictions i.e. Republic of Ireland) have the right to being able to avail of banking services provided by a bank or banks connected to which ethics and int
defaultegrity are unquestionable, where dubious and misleading practices relating to the implying of same and to general fitness and probity standards are not systematic, where third parties i.e. persons working for or providing services to the banks are not subj
defaultected to exploitations, including threats, intimidation, etc, and same re persons who may attempt to expose same and to have the banks acknowledge their complicity, etc.
default&#xa0;
defaultFrom this position it is important, necessary even, that alternative organisations 
defaulti.e. credit unions, other banks, which may operate to levels of integrity and ethics which are higher than those of the traditional Northern Ireland ‘big four’ banks, are able to succeed and progress within the N
defaultorthern Ireland
default banking marketplace
default and to o
defaultffer real and proper choice to banking consumers in Northern Ireland
default, a position which may progress partly to the obstacles to moving bank account which prevailed previously having 
defaultrecently 
defaultbeen removed.
default&#xa0;
defaultI suggest that it is also important that, as referr
defaulted to previously, the NI Affairs Committee seeks to establish some form of 
defaultwhistleblowing facilitydefault for persons within or connected in any shape or form to the NI banking sector i.e. employee, service provider, employee of a service provider to the NI banki
defaultng sector, and not just bank customers, to be able to bring to the attention of 
defaulta relevant body which is completely independent of the banks themselvesdefault, misdemeanours and activities to which entities from within the NI banking sector may be complicit, and 
defaultin connection to which the banks, as has been the case previously and currently, not least as, despite having reference within disingenuous Corporate &amp; Social Responsibility Statements to the availability of 
default‘whistleblowing channedefaultldefaultsdefault’ which are in fact ineffective, the banks are no longer able to operate to an agenda designed to ensure that certain issues i.e. relating to sharp practices, are kept under the radar so to speak, and that there is no longer any sort of misplaced reliance 
defaultin some quarters on the ineffective whistleblowing channels of the banks, channels which, as stated, have been shown not to function as most non bank official individuals would expect, and deliberately so in some, possibly most instances.   
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is no q
defaultuestion that any form of self policing system within the banking sector, for the purpose of this document within the Northern Ireland banking sector, and particularly in respect of the ‘big four’, Bank of Ireland, Danske Bank, First Trust Bank and Ulster B
defaultank, does not work, with such an arrangement shown to be open to abuse and self serving manipulations from within the banking sector.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is a position which is demonstrated by a significant number of acknowledgements to issues raised and assurances th
defaultat those issues will be followed up, only for them to be buried or subject to interference from third party entities, and by the range of tactics readily employed by the banks in relation to attacks of various sorts on the likes of whistleblower(s), a posi
defaulttion which cannot be reconciled with the 
default‘openness and transparency’default defaultand 
default‘high standards’default the banks refer to in disingenuous published Corporate &amp; Social Responsibility Statements and equally disingenuous annual reports and so called Codes of Practice.    
default      
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is a shameful indictment of the levels of integrity and principles of the Northern Ireland ‘big four’ banks, and especially so perhaps with regards to those executives at the top who lead by example and set the corporate tone of those banks whic
defaulth have and continue to participate in the sort of practices referred to, and who are aware of the prevalence of those practices, that all of the details declared within this communication to the Northern Ireland Affairs Committee are true and factual.
defaultTher
defaulte are examples of senior NI bank executives i.e. at Chief Executive level, both in scenarios connected to their high profile banking sector roles and in other high profile non bank roles, implying certain principles, whilst in other areas allowing activiti
defaultes to prevail in their organisations and turning a blind eye to same, which cannot in any circumstances be reconciled with those implied principles.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThere are even examples within banking whereby it is bewildering to some, possibly to many, how when the
default backgrounds of some i.e. the connections and activities to which they have been connected, are considered by relevant regulatory bodies to attain ‘fitness and probity’ standards, in otherwords to be considered fit and proper to hold high office within fin
defaultancially regulated 
defaultorganisations such as banks, when ordinary business owners of much more modest enterprises would, in consideration of their backgrounds, be likely to regard those same individuals as wholly unsuitable i.e. to not be fit and proper, to be
default offered a position, any position, within their modest entrrprise.     
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere are also examples re which it could be suggested the facts cannot easily be reconciled with responsibilities detailed within the general requirements and Fitness and Probity re
defaultquirements deemed to be necessary in senior bank executives i.e. at Chief Executive level, by the relevant UK (and ROI) regulatory bodies.
